
TY  - JOUR
T1  - Hybrid Organizational Arrangements and Their Implications for Firm Growth and Survival: A Study of New Franchisors
AU  - Shane, Scott A.
Y1  - 1996/02/01
PY  - 1996
DA  - 1996/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256637
DO  - 10.5465/256637
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 216
EP  - 234
VL  - 39
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study proposes that hybrid organizational forms provide a way to overcome the agency problems of adverse selection and moral hazard in selecting, assimilating, and monitoring new managers. Consequently, hybrid forms allow firms to overcome managerial limits to firm growth and therefore grow faster. Specifically, the study shows empirically that the degree to which a firm emphasizes franchising as its expansion strategy has a significant, positive effect on its growth and survival.
AB  - This study proposes that hybrid organizational forms provide a way to overcome the agency problems of adverse selection and moral hazard in selecting, assimilating, and monitoring new managers. Consequently, hybrid forms allow firms to overcome managerial limits to firm growth and therefore grow faster. Specifically, the study shows empirically that the degree to which a firm emphasizes franchising as its expansion strategy has a significant, positive effect on its growth and survival.
